econet-eth: fix permanent conduit TX stall under software forwarding

The conduit netdev (eth0) is allocated with 256 TX queues but every one of
them -- and every DSA user-port egress -- funnels into a single hardware
ring, q_tx[0] (en75_dev_xmit() hardcodes qid 0). There is no
ndo_select_queue, so the stack scatters forwarded flows across all 256
queues. Flow control is per-queue: en75_dev_xmit() stops the queue of the
packet that hit a full ring, and en75_poll_tx_complete() wakes only the
queue of the skb it just freed.

The stop path (-EBUSY) returns *before* the skb is posted to the ring, so a
queue stopped on ring-full holds no in-flight descriptor. No future
completion can ever carry that queue's mapping, so its wake condition is
never evaluated; the ring drains via other queues' completions while the
stranded queue stays DRV_XOFF forever. There is no ndo_tx_timeout to reset
it, so it is permanent until reboot. Under sustained software forwarding
(no hardware offload) the ring fills constantly and a high-rate flow keeps
hashing onto the dead queue -- the LAN port freezes at ~150 Mbit/s with
packets stuck in the qdisc. Hardware NAT never hits this: the PPE does the
egress and the conduit ring is barely used.

The gating resource (ring space) is global to all 256 queues, so the wake
must be too. Keep the per-skb BQL accounting, but after the drain loop wake
all of the conduit's queues. netif_tx_wake_all_queues() only clears
DRV_XOFF, not BQL's STACK_XOFF, so the anti-bufferbloat tuning (the BQL
min-limit) is preserved; if the ring re-fills, the next xmit re-stops the
queue and the next completion re-wakes it (self-healing).

Signed-off-by: Cristian Papa <pcristian292@gmail.com>
--- a/econet_qdma.c
+++ b/econet_qdma.c
@@ -1067,6 +1067,7 @@
 	struct qregs_doneq_state state;
 	struct en75_tx_doneq *done_q;
 	struct en75_qdma *qdma;
+	struct net_device *wake_dev = NULL;
 	int id, irq_queued;
 	u32 done = 0, head;
 
@@ -1138,13 +1139,28 @@
 			txq = netdev_get_tx_queue(skb->dev,
 						  skb_get_queue_mapping(skb));
 			netdev_tx_completed_queue(txq, 1, skb->len);
-			if (netif_tx_queue_stopped(txq))
-				netif_tx_wake_queue(txq);
+			/* All of this netdev's TX queues funnel into the single
+			 * HW ring q_tx[0]; the gating resource (ring space) is
+			 * shared. A queue stopped on ring-full holds no
+			 * descriptor of its own (en75_qdma_xmit returns -EBUSY
+			 * before posting the skb), so it can never generate a
+			 * completion to wake itself -> permanent stall. Defer a
+			 * device-wide wake to after the drain loop instead of the
+			 * per-queue wake. */
+			wake_dev = skb->dev;
 		}
 
 		dev_kfree_skb_any(skb);
 	}
 
+	/* Freed at least one ring slot: wake every TX queue of the conduit so
+	 * the descriptor-less stranded queue(s) restart. netif_tx_wake_all_queues
+	 * only clears DRV_XOFF (not BQL's STACK_XOFF), so the BQL throttle from
+	 * patch 330 is preserved; if the ring re-fills, the next xmit re-stops
+	 * the queue and the next completion re-wakes it (self-healing). */
+	if (wake_dev)
+		netif_tx_wake_all_queues(wake_dev);
+
 	if (done) {
 		int i, len = done >> 7;
 
